    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Unity Is Not Enough</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By John Shaw</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Large cheering squad of South Koreans supports Kye Sun Hui of North Korea during her judo match against Cuba's Legna Verdecia, but Verdecia wins match at Sydney Olympics (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Kye Sun Hui of North Korea, the defending gold medalist in the 52-kilogram judo division, yesterday was supported by a large, surprising cheering squad -- a jet-load of South Koreans who were supporting national unity as well as Kye.</p>
        <p>Unfortunately, the cheers weren't enough to help Kye keep her title. Her title slipped away later in a semifinal upset by Cuba's Legna Verdecia, who went on to win the gold with a victory over Noriko Narazaki of Japan in the championship match.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Kye Sun Hui of North Korea, the defending gold medalist in the 52-kilogram judo division, yesterday was supported by a large, surprising cheering squad -- a jet-load of South Koreans who were supporting national unity as well as Kye.</p>
        <p>Unfortunately, the cheers weren't enough to help Kye keep her title. Her title slipped away later in a semifinal upset by Cuba's Legna Verdecia, who went on to win the gold with a victory over Noriko Narazaki of Japan in the championship match.</p>
        <p>But early on, 400 chanting, stamping, flag-waving Seoul residents came right off their charter flight and arrived just in time to see Kye defeat Hillary Wolf, an American actress turned athlete. The tourists staged a ''Unite Korea'' demonstration, echoing the joint North-South team march at Friday's opening ceremony.</p>
        <p>Seung Choon Ahn, executive vice president of Korea Telecom, co-sponsor of the tour, said it was arranged months ago as a promotion. ''When moves for South-North unification began, we decided the Olympics was a good place to show support,'' he said. Like his companions, he had a baseball cap, T-shirt and flag with the blue and white logos of a map of all Korea.</p>
        <p>John Shaw</p>
        <p>SYDNEY 2000: JUDO</p>
      </block>
